{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "NYISO generation interconnection process fees UG21 manual 23",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "NYISO",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "ce8d5e86-faca-4b04-999f-fb7f9f75e199",
        "score": 0.5999798,
        "text": "The document page provides an analysis of cost-minimizing output levels for a generator, focusing on bid costs, total production costs, and average costs at different output levels (20 MW, 40 MW, and 50 MW). \n\n- **Output Levels and Costs:**\n  - At 20 MW, the total production cost is $1500, with an average cost of $75/MWh and an adjusted offer curve of $57.5/MWh.\n  - At 40 MW, the total production cost is $2300, with an average and adjusted offer curve cost of $57.5/MWh.\n  - At 50 MW, the total production cost is $2900, with an average cost of $58/MWh and an adjusted offer curve of $60/MWh.\n\n- **Cost-Minimizing Output:**\n  - The cost-minimizing output level is identified as 40 MW, with a minimum average cost of $57.5/MWh.\n\n- **Adjusted Dispatch Cost:**\n  - For outputs up to 40 MW, the adjusted dispatch cost is $57.5/MWh.\n  - For outputs above 40 MW up to 50 MW, the cost is $60/MWh.\n\n- **Example 2: RT Injection:**\n  - Parameters for a real-time market example include minimum generation cost ($4000/hr), minimum generation level (90 MW), upper operating limit (100 MW), start-up cost ($400), and incremental energy costs for different output increases.\n\nThis page is part of a Transmission and Dispatch Operations Manual, focusing on optimizing generation costs and dispatch strategies.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Transmission_and_Dispatch_Operations_Manual/page_164.jpg",
          "page_num": 164,
          "title": "Transmission and Dispatch Operations Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8ecdb3f8-11f2-4f49-a085-e78469e5814c",
        "score": 0.59489834,
        "text": "The document discusses \"Guarantee Payment Uplift Charges\" in the New York electricity market. These charges are used to recover additional payments not covered by Locational Based Marginal Prices (LBMPs) and other revenues. The charges are difficult to hedge and lack transparency, so minimizing them is crucial for efficient market operation.\n\nIn 2022, the total guarantee payment uplift was $94 million, a 74% increase from 2021, primarily due to higher gas prices and increased commitment costs for gas-fired units. New York City accounted for $50 million, or 53% of the total uplift, marking a 92% increase from 2021. A significant portion, over $36 million, was paid to generators committed for local reliability requirements. The document includes a figure showing uplift costs by region and category for 2021 and 2022.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2022/page_102.jpg",
          "page_num": 102,
          "title": "2022 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9f37933d-ed50-4c6b-bfd6-31f213fb9caf",
        "score": 0.58867174,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the sale and purchase of Unforced Capacity in the New York ISO market. Key points include:\n\n1. **Market-Clearing Prices**: \n   - Sellers of Unforced Capacity are paid based on the Market-Clearing Price for their locality, the New York Control Area (NYCA), or an external control area, multiplied by the number of megawatts (MW) of accepted offers.\n\n2. **ICAP Spot Market Auction**: \n   - Entities purchasing Unforced Capacity are charged according to the Market-Clearing Price as detailed in Section 5.15 of the ICAP Manual.\n\n3. **Billing and Payment Schedule**: \n   - Settlements occur in the month following the purchase. For example, capacity bought in May is billed in June. The billing schedule aligns with the Energy Market schedule, available on the NYISO website.\n\n4. **Six-Month Strip Auction**: \n   - Unforced Capacity purchased in this auction is settled monthly, with bills issued for one-sixth of the applicable Market-Clearing Price.\n\n5. **Allocation of Winning Bids**: \n   - During Capability Period and Monthly Auctions, bidders specifying a locality for their Unforced Capacity will receive a pro rata share of the purchased capacity.\n\nThis document is part of the Installed Capacity Manual, providing detailed guidelines for market participants.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_243.jpg",
          "page_num": 243,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "52cdc694-7175-4e15-b8ee-5b826d52c721",
        "score": 0.5846188,
        "text": "The document discusses \"Variable Cost Data\" related to operating and maintenance costs for generators.\n\n### 8.1 General Description\n\n#### 8.1.1 Operating Costs\n- Operating costs are non-fuel expenses incurred during generator operation, including start-up and various output levels.\n- Examples include labor, consumables, non-durable goods, and water costs.\n- NYISO approves only incremental operating costs, rejecting fixed costs.\n- Approval is based on whether costs reflect the incremental stage of the power generation cycle.\n- Costs must be reasonable, industry-standard, and align with manufacturer expectations.\n- Case-by-case evaluations are conducted, considering factors like generator start-up and operating levels.\n\n#### 8.1.2 Maintenance Costs\n- Maintenance costs cover the upkeep of generation resources and equipment.\n- Approval is for costs resulting from incremental usage periods.\n- Costs are a share of future maintenance, allocated using hours-based or equivalent criteria.\n- They should reflect projected costs and be based on anticipated generator usage.\n- Suppliers must provide manufacturer recommendations on maintenance periodicity and relevant factors.\n- NYISO considers if maintenance costs and frequency align with manufacturer expectations and practical usage scenarios.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_36.jpg",
          "page_num": 36,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9dc9cb80-882a-4c59-b88c-d8af5cc02fcd",
        "score": 0.58329624,
        "text": "The document page outlines guidelines for suppliers submitting cost-based references related to regulatory and operational costs for generators. \n\n1. **Regulatory Costs**: Suppliers can include documented regulatory costs assessed by NYISO in their cost-based references.\n\n2. **RLS Data Requirements**: Suppliers may submit variable operation and maintenance (O&M) costs and other variable costs per output level. Each submission must include a description of the requested costs. Suppliers can also submit regulatory and related costs separately.\n\n3. **Required Documentation**: Suppliers must provide detailed methodology, data, and calculations for the variable costs submitted. The data should be generator-specific, detailing incremental operation costs like starts, run-hours, or MWhs generated. Historical costs can substantiate variable O&M costs, provided they match the periodicity of claimed maintenance. Suppliers should submit at least three years of supporting data for costs claimed every three years. \n\n   - Suppliers can index cost submittals using historic time-series data, providing both raw and indexed data with a rationale for the index used.\n   - Unplanned maintenance costs should be projected based on risks and historical data, typically over a seven-year period, and calculated per start or per MWh.\n\n4. **Long-Term Service Agreements (LTSAs)**: Suppliers may use LTSAs to support maintenance costs if they align with approved variable costs. Each component's dollar value in long-term maintenance must be clearly defined.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_37.jpg",
          "page_num": 37,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0f30e51f-0fce-4142-8d03-36172866ad45",
        "score": 0.5820799,
        "text": "The document page is from the New York ISO and discusses the setting of the Market-Clearing Price for Unforced Capacity in the NYCA (New York Control Area). It states that the lower of $6/kW-month or $5/kW-month will be used for this purpose. This price applies to all localities within the NYCA, as there are no binding locality constraints in this example.\n\nThe page includes \"Example 6,\" which features two graphs. The left graph shows the supply (S) and demand (D) curves for control areas P and Q, with a price of $2/kW-month at the intersection. The right graph shows the supply and demand curves for the NYCA, with a price of $5/kW-month at the intersection. Both graphs plot price ($/kW-month) against megawatts (MW).",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual_Attachments/page_31.jpg",
          "page_num": 31,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual Attachments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0f4e4c04-660d-4344-a06e-7957b5a3fcff",
        "score": 0.58056426,
        "text": "The document discusses several key issues related to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) and its operations:\n\n1. **Export Fees and CTS Transactions**: NYISO's high export fees, amounting to $0.8 million in 2021, may reduce revenues from Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) transactions. Lower fees could increase profitability. The document suggests reducing transaction fees and uplift charges between PJM and NYISO to improve effectiveness.\n\n2. **Price Forecast Errors**: Errors at interfaces affect the effectiveness of CTS processes. Improving these processes is crucial for handling renewable output growth and balancing short-term fluctuations in intermittent generation.\n\n3. **PAR-Controlled Lines**: Phase angle regulators (PARs) are used to manage production costs. The operation of lines between Long Island and New York City increased costs and emissions in 2021. The report recommends exploring changes to the ConEd-LIPA wheeling agreement to enhance efficiency, especially with the growth of offshore wind and intermittent generation.\n\n4. **Out-of-Market Actions**: Guarantee payments to generators increased by 28% to $54 million in 2021, mainly due to higher natural gas prices. This was partially offset by reduced out-of-market commitments and dispatches.\n\nOverall, the document emphasizes the need for operational improvements and cost reductions to enhance efficiency and accommodate renewable energy growth.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2021/page_16.jpg",
          "page_num": 16,
          "title": "2021 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4f1e828c-ec3b-42c5-ba1a-df30ca3fddac",
        "score": 0.5795124,
        "text": "The document outlines the adjusted offer curve for a generator after the first 15 minutes of operation. It provides a table with different output levels (90 MW, 91 MW, 95 MW, 100 MW), their corresponding bid costs, total production costs, average costs, and adjusted offer curves.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- The cost-minimizing output level after 15 minutes is 95 MW, with a minimum average cost of $44.11/MWh.\n- For output levels up to 95 MW, the adjusted dispatch cost is $44.11/MWh, based on the average as-offered cost.\n- For outputs above 95 MW, up to 100 MW, the adjusted dispatch cost is $50.00/MWh, based on the generator's bid.\n- The NYISO uses a procedure to determine an adjusted offer curve for online Fast-Start Resources, focusing on maximizing the average as-offered cost, referred to as the \"AC-maximizing output level.\"\n- For output levels greater than or equal to the AC-maximizing level, the adjusted offer curve price is set to the maximum average cost.\n- The start-up cost applies to the first hour of operation in the Day-Ahead Market and the first 15 minutes in the Real-Time Market.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Transmission_and_Dispatch_Operations_Manual/page_166.jpg",
          "page_num": 166,
          "title": "Transmission and Dispatch Operations Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "febf78bb-abed-4ab8-8531-1859fb33b1cd",
        "score": 0.57833695,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2023 State of the Market Report\" and focuses on \"Regulation Market Performance.\" It includes Figure A-22, which illustrates regulation prices and expenses for each month over the past two years. The upper part of the figure compares regulation prices in the day-ahead (DA) and real-time (RT) markets, while the lower part summarizes regulation costs to NYISO customers.\n\nKey components include:\n\n- **Day-Ahead Capacity Charge**: Calculated as the day-ahead capacity clearing price times the regulation capacity procured in the day-ahead market.\n- **Real-Time Shortage Rebate**: Occurs when a regulation shortage happens in the real-time market, requiring suppliers to buy back the shortage at real-time prices.\n- **Movement Charge**: Compensation for regulation resources to provide service, calculated based on the real-time movement price, instructed regulation movement, and a performance factor.\n\nThe table and graph show:\n\n- **2022**: DA price at $16.26/MW, RT price at $11.25/MW, with total expenses of $30.2 million.\n- **2023**: DA price at $9.16/MW, RT price at $8.69/MW, with total expenses of $19.9 million.\n\nThe chart visually represents these prices and expenses, highlighting the components of regulation costs.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_202.jpg",
          "page_num": 202,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ef466c90-4b42-4bca-88af-e67fc550132d",
        "score": 0.57639205,
        "text": "The document discusses the NYISO's approach to managing guarantee payment uplift charges, which are additional payments to market participants not covered by LBMP and other revenues. These charges are challenging to hedge and can obscure economic signals. The document emphasizes minimizing these charges to ensure efficient market operations.\n\nIn 2021, guarantee payment uplifts totaled $54 million, a 28% increase from 2020, mainly due to higher gas prices affecting gas-fired units. New York City accounted for $26 million of these charges, with a significant portion paid to generators committed for local reliability needs. Recommendations include modeling local reserve requirements to reduce these uplifts and improve price transparency.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2021/page_78.jpg",
          "page_num": 78,
          "title": "2021 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

