        "score": 0.56182957,
        "text": "The document outlines requirements for establishing communication between a DSASP Provider and the New York ISO. Key points include:\n\n1. **Communication Configuration**:\n   - Required if the DSASP Provider's total enrollment is \u2264 25 MW.\n   - Involves one communications vendor, a set of network components, and one ICCP node.\n   - The DSASP Provider and NYISO must complete vendor agreements for direct communications.\n\n2. **Hardware and Software Requirements**:\n   - Establish a contract with a communications vendor to link to NYISO.\n   - Select circuit type, bandwidth, and obtain a Virtual Private LAN Service or MPLS.\n   - Identify network hardware, ensuring routers support encryption and firewalls are recommended.\n   - Software must support ICCP communication as both client and server.\n   - Configure hardware/software for ICCP Node, collaborating with NYISO personnel.\n   - Ensure scalability and redundancy, with systems designed for 99.99% availability.\n   - Identify necessary servers and hardware based on software vendor requirements.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Manual_2_Ancillary_Services_Manual/page_91.jpg",
          "page_num": 91,
          "title": "Manual 2 Ancillary Services Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c7f7e1ea-c08e-41ea-b01d-dcd29aa88bd9",
        "score": 0.5585104,
        "text": "The document page is from the New York ISO Aggregation Manual and includes a table of contents for sections 5 to 7. Here's a summary:\n\n### Section 5: Transmission Nodes\n- **5.1**: Discusses member system topology considerations and the active transmission node list.\n- **5.2**: Covers transmission node changes, including the change timeline.\n- **5.3**: Details DER (Distributed Energy Resource) designation to a transmission node and related changes.\n- **5.4**: Focuses on transmission node operations.\n- **5.5**: Outlines aggregator responsibilities.\n\n### Section 6: Operational Coordination\n- **6.1**: Describes operating data exchange, including planned and unplanned system maintenance, market bids, outage reporting, and dispatch instructions.\n- **6.2**: Defines roles and responsibilities, emphasizing communication between various entities like distribution utilities, transmission owners, aggregators, and NYISO.\n- **6.3**: Provides a coordination timeline for dispatch activities, detailing specific timeframes for actions before and after dispatch.\n\n### Section 7: Metering & Telemetry\n- **7.1**: Offers background information.\n- **7.2**: Lists metering requirements.\n- **7.3**: Details telemetry requirements, including a specific telemetry testing procedure for NYISO-member systems.\n\nThis page outlines the structure and key topics covered in these sections of the manual.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Aggregation_Manual/page_4.jpg",
          "page_num": 4,
          "title": "Aggregation Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6b33df2d-f018-4515-b9c7-718d3e9b1b71",
        "score": 0.55592024,
        "text": "The document is a section from an agreement related to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) and its market participants. It includes the following key points:\n\n1. **Liability Release**: Market participants release NYISO and its affiliates from liability, except in cases of gross negligence or intentional misconduct.\n\n2. **Miscellaneous Provisions**:\n   - **Communications**: Details how inquiries, notices, and communications should be exchanged between NYISO and market participants, including contact information for NYISO.\n   - **Survival of Terms**: All representations, warranties, covenants, and obligations remain effective beyond the purchase or sale of Unforced Capacity.\n   - **Entire Agreement**: The agreement, along with the ICAP Manual and ISO Services Tariff, constitutes the full agreement, superseding prior discussions.\n   - **Enforcement**: The agreement's provisions are enforceable for the benefit of both parties.\n   - **Governing Law**: The agreement is governed by New York State law, without regard to conflict of laws provisions.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual_Attachments/page_19.jpg",
          "page_num": 19,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual Attachments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9f37933d-ed50-4c6b-bfd6-31f213fb9caf",
        "score": 0.5537554,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the sale and purchase of Unforced Capacity in the New York ISO market. Key points include:\n\n1. **Market-Clearing Prices**: \n   - Sellers of Unforced Capacity are paid based on the Market-Clearing Price for their locality, the New York Control Area (NYCA), or an external control area, multiplied by the number of megawatts (MW) of accepted offers.\n\n2. **ICAP Spot Market Auction**: \n   - Entities purchasing Unforced Capacity are charged according to the Market-Clearing Price as detailed in Section 5.15 of the ICAP Manual.\n\n3. **Billing and Payment Schedule**: \n   - Settlements occur in the month following the purchase. For example, capacity bought in May is billed in June. The billing schedule aligns with the Energy Market schedule, available on the NYISO website.\n\n4. **Six-Month Strip Auction**: \n   - Unforced Capacity purchased in this auction is settled monthly, with bills issued for one-sixth of the applicable Market-Clearing Price.\n\n5. **Allocation of Winning Bids**: \n   - During Capability Period and Monthly Auctions, bidders specifying a locality for their Unforced Capacity will receive a pro rata share of the purchased capacity.\n\nThis document is part of the Installed Capacity Manual, providing detailed guidelines for market participants.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_243.jpg",
          "page_num": 243,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0f30e51f-0fce-4142-8d03-36172866ad45",
        "score": 0.5509436,
        "text": "The document page is from the New York ISO and discusses the setting of the Market-Clearing Price for Unforced Capacity in the NYCA (New York Control Area). It states that the lower of $6/kW-month or $5/kW-month will be used for this purpose. This price applies to all localities within the NYCA, as there are no binding locality constraints in this example.\n\nThe page includes \"Example 6,\" which features two graphs. The left graph shows the supply (S) and demand (D) curves for control areas P and Q, with a price of $2/kW-month at the intersection. The right graph shows the supply and demand curves for the NYCA, with a price of $5/kW-month at the intersection. Both graphs plot price ($/kW-month) against megawatts (MW).",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual_Attachments/page_31.jpg",
          "page_num": 31,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual Attachments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b164d87f-9ccf-468c-8cb0-176f30fb3261",
        "score": 0.54498094,
        "text": "The document page discusses the requirements for suppliers to provide the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) with documentation of costs related to maintenance activities as defined in the Long-Term Service Agreement (LTSA). It specifies that suppliers can include cost escalators in their submissions if they are part of the LTSA. Suppliers must submit contracts to demonstrate the variability of costs, which are subject to review by NYISO and its Market Monitoring Unit (MMU) for reasonableness and appropriateness. The NYISO allows the inclusion of certain costs, like fuel management fees, in cost-based references when presented on a per mmBTU basis.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_38.jpg",
          "page_num": 38,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "14a3f2e3-fafe-4901-874e-a94ec44c6355",
        "score": 0.540462,
        "text": "This document page discusses deliverability and transmission planning related to the interconnection of energy projects, focusing on the categories of upgrades identified in the Cluster Study and Class Year process. The key points include:\n\n1. **Categories of Upgrades:**\n   - **Connecting Transmission Owner\u2019s Attachment Facilities (CTOAF):** Facilities required to connect a project to the transmission owner's network.\n   - **System Upgrade Facilities (SUF):** Network upgrades needed for projects to comply with NYISO\u2019s Minimum Interconnection Standard (MIS). Projects must pay allocated costs to receive the right to sell energy (ERIS). The MIS addresses reliability impacts but allows normal operating actions to avoid adverse effects.\n   - **System Deliverability Upgrades (SDU):** Upgrades required for resources to be deliverable under NYISO\u2019s Deliverability Interconnection Standard (DIS). Projects must pay for these upgrades to receive the right to sell capacity (CRIS). The DIS ensures that new and existing resources can deliver output without violating transmission constraints.\n\n2. **Process and Costs:**\n   - Developers must decide whether to pay for upgrades to receive ERIS or CRIS rights or withdraw from the study.\n   - The number of resources seeking interconnection and upgrade costs have increased recently.\n   - Class Year studies typically take about two years, while the Cluster Study aims for a 590-day timeline.\n   - New resources not part of an ongoing study must wait for a new study to begin.\n   - If SDUs are needed, a preliminary cost estimate is issued, and affected projects may enter an Additional SDU Study for final cost allocations.\n\n3. **Inefficient Upgrade Project Selection \u2013 Class Year 2023:**\n   - The most recent Class Year study (2023) started in January 2023 and finished in early 2025.\n   - Participants requested about 15 GW of ERIS and 14 GW of CRIS.\n   - The study identified $2.8 billion in CTOAF and SUF costs, with individual cost allocations ranging from $0 to $581 per kW of nameplate capacity, averaging $207 per kW.\n   - Proposed projects were generally fully deliverable except on Long Island, where an Additional SDU Study was necessary.\n\nThe page also includes references to additional details on the interconnection process and related study reports available on NYISO\u2019s website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/NYISO/report/2024/page_50.jpg",
          "page_num": 50,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d5b29f8d-c4cf-4d57-a755-1f6969f46e53",
        "score": 0.5404569,
        "text": "The document page outlines the annual budget charge and other non-budget charges and payments for services provided by the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). It categorizes these charges into three main areas: \n\n1. **Physical Operation of the NY Control Area**\n2. **Administration of NYISO tariffs and related agreements**\n3. **Other Non-Budget Charges**\n\nDetails of these services are found in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the Accounting and Billing Manual.\n\n**Recovery of NYISO Costs**: Information on cost recovery is available in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the NYISO Services Tariff.\n\n**Payment for Service**: Payment details are also in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the NYISO Services Tariff.\n\n**Services at the Request of a Market Participant**: Market participants can request and pay for specific NYISO services, including:\n\n- System Reliability Impact Study (ESRIS)\n- Facilities Study\n- Local Control Center operator training\n- Re-enforcement Option Study (also requested by PSC)\n- System Impact Study\n- Interconnection Study",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Manual_2_Ancillary_Services_Manual/page_36.jpg",
          "page_num": 36,
          "title": "Manual 2 Ancillary Services Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "154fabdc-bfab-42a1-936f-630e45868f98",
        "score": 0.54008245,
        "text": "The document page is from the New York ISO Transmission Congestion Contracts Manual. It discusses the provision of rules, procedures, and guidelines for new auction formats. The section titled \"References\" lists documents and resources available on the NYISO website that provide additional background or details related to the manual. These include:\n\n- Open Access Transmission Tariff\n- NYISO Market Administration and Control Area Services Tariff\n- NYISO Accounting and Billing Manual\n- Transmission Congestion Contracts page\n- NYISO Customer Registration\n- TCC Automated Market System User\u2019s Guide\n- Credit Management System User\u2019s Guide\n- Settlement Data Applications User\u2019s Guide\n\nThese resources are intended to support understanding and implementation of the manual's content.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Transmission_Congestion_Contracts_Manual/page_24.jpg",
          "page_num": 24,
          "title": "Transmission Congestion Contracts Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b29e033b-f5aa-4591-9721-45a301caa65c",
        "score": 0.5389267,
        "text": "The document page is from the New York ISO's Transmission and Dispatch Operations Manual. It is titled \"Attachment A Transmission Facilities\" and outlines three tables:\n\n1. **Table A.1**: Lists NYISO facilities that require coordination and notification.\n2. **Table A.2**: Lists bus voltage limits.\n3. **Table A.3**: Lists bus voltage limits specifically for HQ-NYISO transfers.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Transmission_and_Dispatch_Operations_Manual/page_153.jpg",
          "page_num": 153,
          "title": "Transmission and Dispatch Operations Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

