        "score": 0.56146693,
        "text": "The document page discusses the requirements for suppliers to provide the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) with documentation of costs related to maintenance activities as defined in the Long-Term Service Agreement (LTSA). It specifies that suppliers can include cost escalators in their submissions if they are part of the LTSA. Suppliers must submit contracts to demonstrate the variability of costs, which are subject to review by NYISO and its Market Monitoring Unit (MMU) for reasonableness and appropriateness. The NYISO allows the inclusion of certain costs, like fuel management fees, in cost-based references when presented on a per mmBTU basis.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_38.jpg",
          "page_num": 38,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a862ff48-cdb9-4302-9b35-efad7297a369",
        "score": 0.5565646,
        "text": "The document discusses differences in Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) processes at the NY/PJM and NY/NE interfaces, focusing on fees and their impact on scheduling efficiency. \n\n1. **NYISO vs. PJM Charges**:\n   - NYISO charges for physical exports to PJM range from $6 to $7/MWh, while PJM charges less than $2/MWh for imports and exports.\n   - PJM also charges for \"real-time deviations\" at a rate averaging less than $1/MWh.\n   - These charges create economic barriers, deterring price-sensitive CTS bids at the NY/PJM border.\n\n2. **ISO-NE Border**:\n   - Most transactions cleared at less than $5/MWh, with average profits slightly over $1/MWh in 2019.\n   - NYISO charges for exports to PJM are expected to exceed $5/MWh, affecting the liquidity of the CTS process.\n\n3. **Production Cost Savings**:\n   - Savings decreased from $5.5 million in 2018 to $4.1 million in 2019 due to smaller energy price differences, influenced by lower natural gas prices and load levels.\n   - Price forecasting improved at the NY/NE border, with reduced forecast errors.\n   - Minimal savings at the PJM border were noted despite projected savings, largely due to significant forecasting errors.\n\nThe document suggests eliminating charges on CTS transactions at the NY/PJM interface to improve performance.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2019/page_271.jpg",
          "page_num": 271,
          "title": "2019 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d5b29f8d-c4cf-4d57-a755-1f6969f46e53",
        "score": 0.5551121,
        "text": "The document page outlines the annual budget charge and other non-budget charges and payments for services provided by the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). It categorizes these charges into three main areas: \n\n1. **Physical Operation of the NY Control Area**\n2. **Administration of NYISO tariffs and related agreements**\n3. **Other Non-Budget Charges**\n\nDetails of these services are found in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the Accounting and Billing Manual.\n\n**Recovery of NYISO Costs**: Information on cost recovery is available in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the NYISO Services Tariff.\n\n**Payment for Service**: Payment details are also in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the NYISO Services Tariff.\n\n**Services at the Request of a Market Participant**: Market participants can request and pay for specific NYISO services, including:\n\n- System Reliability Impact Study (ESRIS)\n- Facilities Study\n- Local Control Center operator training\n- Re-enforcement Option Study (also requested by PSC)\n- System Impact Study\n- Interconnection Study",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Manual_2_Ancillary_Services_Manual/page_36.jpg",
          "page_num": 36,
          "title": "Manual 2 Ancillary Services Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4b1f14bc-1d8b-4123-9aed-cc9c714ab763",
        "score": 0.55344176,
        "text": "The document discusses the impact of fees on transactions between control areas, specifically between New York and New England. In 2005, export fees between these regions were eliminated to facilitate market arbitrage, but other charges remain. These charges, related to ISO/RTO operating costs, were initially based on the largest transaction of the month, leading to high costs for some participants. To address this, an alternative per MWh allocation method was introduced. Despite these changes, significant price dispersion and seams issues persist, hindering efficient market interchange. The document highlights the importance of efficient scheduling during peak demand and examines price differences in unconstrained hours when prices exceed $200/MWh.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2005/page_145.jpg",
          "page_num": 145,
          "title": "2005 State of the Market Report New York ISO",
          "year": 2005,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f570ecb6-5175-4904-88aa-d1cc509df9a4",
        "score": 0.551157,
        "text": "The document discusses the differences in Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) processes at the NY/PJM and NY/NE interfaces, focusing on the impact of fees and charges. Key points include:\n\n- **Charges and Economic Barriers**: NYISO charges for exports to PJM range from $4 to $8/MWh, while PJM charges less than $2/MWh for imports and exports. PJM also charges for \"real-time deviations\" at less than $1/MWh. These charges create economic barriers, deterring price-sensitive CTS bids at the NY/PJM border.\n\n- **Transaction Patterns**: Most transactions at the ISO-NE border cleared at less than $5/MWh. The uncertainty and potential high charges from PJM discourage CTS transactions above this price.\n\n- **Savings Analysis**: In 2016, projected production cost savings were $4.5 million at NY/NE and $3.1 million at NY/PJM. However, actual savings were lower due to forecast errors, with $2 million realized at NY/NE and none at NY/PJM.\n\n- **Efficiency and Forecast Errors**: The analysis suggests that inefficiencies arise when forecast errors exceed $20/MWh. Savings align more closely with projections when errors are moderate.\n\nThe document recommends eliminating charges at the NY/PJM interface to improve the efficiency of the CTS process.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2016/page_222.jpg",
          "page_num": 222,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2016,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1d89cf8f-50ba-48fa-bcfe-9d2457c11e03",
        "score": 0.5501493,
        "text": "The document page discusses the profitability and quantity of scheduled real-time external transactions between PJM and NE primary interfaces from 2017 to 2021. It includes a bar graph showing the 5-year average profit and scheduled megawatts (MW) for imports and exports between NY/NE and NY/PJM.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Recommendation to Reduce Charges**: The document suggests eliminating or reducing charges at PJM interfaces to improve efficiency. This is crucial as New York's energy mix shifts towards more intermittent renewable resources, necessitating better scheduling to neighboring regions.\n\n2. **Transmission Charges**: It argues against applying the same transmission charges to price-sensitive exports as to network load customers, as these exports do not contribute to the transmission system's cost.\n\n3. **Export Fees**: In 2021, NYISO collected $0.8 million in export fees from real-time exports to PJM, while PJM collected $1.7 million from exports to NYISO. Lowering export fees could increase overall fee collection by making Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) transactions more profitable under various conditions.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2021/page_121.jpg",
          "page_num": 121,
          "title": "2021 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "14a3f2e3-fafe-4901-874e-a94ec44c6355",
        "score": 0.5481916,
        "text": "This document page discusses deliverability and transmission planning related to the interconnection of energy projects, focusing on the categories of upgrades identified in the Cluster Study and Class Year process. The key points include:\n\n1. **Categories of Upgrades:**\n   - **Connecting Transmission Owner\u2019s Attachment Facilities (CTOAF):** Facilities required to connect a project to the transmission owner's network.\n   - **System Upgrade Facilities (SUF):** Network upgrades needed for projects to comply with NYISO\u2019s Minimum Interconnection Standard (MIS). Projects must pay allocated costs to receive the right to sell energy (ERIS). The MIS addresses reliability impacts but allows normal operating actions to avoid adverse effects.\n   - **System Deliverability Upgrades (SDU):** Upgrades required for resources to be deliverable under NYISO\u2019s Deliverability Interconnection Standard (DIS). Projects must pay for these upgrades to receive the right to sell capacity (CRIS). The DIS ensures that new and existing resources can deliver output without violating transmission constraints.\n\n2. **Process and Costs:**\n   - Developers must decide whether to pay for upgrades to receive ERIS or CRIS rights or withdraw from the study.\n   - The number of resources seeking interconnection and upgrade costs have increased recently.\n   - Class Year studies typically take about two years, while the Cluster Study aims for a 590-day timeline.\n   - New resources not part of an ongoing study must wait for a new study to begin.\n   - If SDUs are needed, a preliminary cost estimate is issued, and affected projects may enter an Additional SDU Study for final cost allocations.\n\n3. **Inefficient Upgrade Project Selection \u2013 Class Year 2023:**\n   - The most recent Class Year study (2023) started in January 2023 and finished in early 2025.\n   - Participants requested about 15 GW of ERIS and 14 GW of CRIS.\n   - The study identified $2.8 billion in CTOAF and SUF costs, with individual cost allocations ranging from $0 to $581 per kW of nameplate capacity, averaging $207 per kW.\n   - Proposed projects were generally fully deliverable except on Long Island, where an Additional SDU Study was necessary.\n\nThe page also includes references to additional details on the interconnection process and related study reports available on NYISO\u2019s website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/NYISO/report/2024/page_50.jpg",
          "page_num": 50,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6b3f612e-09f8-4ead-9fdc-93336dbcb757",
        "score": 0.5424196,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2011 State of the Market Report\" and focuses on Transmission Congestion Contracts (TCC) costs and profits by path type for the Winter 2010/11 and Summer 2011 capability periods. \n\n### Key Points:\n\n1. **Figure A-46 Overview:**\n   - The figure displays TCC profit, cost, and profit as a percentage of value for inter-zone and intra-zone paths.\n   - Inter-zone paths show a total cost of $106 million and a profit of $39 million, with a profit percentage of 27%.\n   - Intra-zone paths show a total cost of $32 million and a profit of $17 million, with a profit percentage of 34%.\n\n2. **TCC Prices and Day-ahead Congestion:**\n   - The analysis compares TCC clearing prices with day-ahead market congestion prices at the zonal level for 2011.\n   - **One-year TCC prices:** Based on four auction rounds in August and September 2010.\n   - **Six-month TCC prices:** Sum of average prices from three Winter and four Summer Capability Period Auctions.\n   - **Reconfiguration TCC prices:** Sum from six monthly reconfiguration auctions during Winter and Summer.\n   - **Day-ahead congestion prices:** Total congestion prices in the day-ahead market for the 12-month period.\n\nThis analysis helps evaluate the consistency of TCC auction prices with actual congestion costs in the market.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2011/page_132.jpg",
          "page_num": 132,
          "title": "2011 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2011,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "75592854-0a16-45ec-a8af-564f70baa40d",
        "score": 0.54235566,
        "text": "The document page contains two tables and a section discussing financial transmission rights.\n\n**Table A-5: TCC Cost by Path**\n- Displays the Transmission Congestion Contract (TCC) costs for various paths during the Winter 2020/21 and Summer 2021 capability periods.\n- Costs are listed for different paths such as WEST, GENESE, CENTRAL, and others, with a total cost of $253.\n\n**Table A-6: TCC Profit by Path**\n- Shows the TCC profits for the same paths and periods.\n- Profits are calculated similarly, with a total profit of $66.\n\n**Section J: Potential Design of Financial Transmission Rights for PAR Operation**\n- Discusses creating a financial right to compensate ConEd if lines between NYC and Long Island are scheduled efficiently.\n- The financial right should compensate based on marginal production cost savings and ensure no uplift for NYISO customers.\n- The concept emphasizes that the right should reflect the marginal cost of relieving congestion, aligning with how generators and customers are charged.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2021/page_245.jpg",
          "page_num": 245,
          "title": "2021 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "fd40effc-37d8-4e2e-8c20-c9bf4b34acd7",
        "score": 0.5422094,
        "text": "The document page presents data on Transmission Congestion Contracts (TCC) costs and profits for intra-zone and inter-zone paths during the Winter 2022/23 and Summer 2023 capability periods. It includes a figure and tables summarizing TCC costs, profits, and profitability percentages for different auction rounds and path types.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- **Inter-Zone TCCs**: \n  - Total cost: $706 million\n  - Total profit: -$523 million\n  - Profitability: -74%\n  - Breakdown by period: One Year, Six-Month Winter, Six-Month Summer, and Monthly, with varying costs and negative profits.\n\n- **Intra-Zone TCCs**:\n  - Total cost: $70 million\n  - Total profit: $14 million\n  - Profitability: 20%\n  - Breakdown by period: One Year, Six-Month Winter, Six-Month Summer, and Monthly, with varying costs and profits.\n\nThe tables highlight TCC costs and profits, with values above $2 million marked in green and those below -$2 million in light red. The analysis covers a 12-month period from November 2022 to October 2023, comparing paths with different Points of Injection (POI) and Points of Withdrawal (POW).",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_247.jpg",
          "page_num": 247,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

