{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "\"UG21\" \"Manual 23\" interconnection process NYISO",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "NYISO",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "ac6d61c9-86f0-4401-96ec-0453922296a1",
        "score": 0.5916314,
        "text": "The document outlines the interconnection process for Distributed Energy Resources (DER) facilities with the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). Interconnection is allowed through the NYISO Small Generator Interconnection Procedure (SGIP) or other approved procedures. Interconnection studies must be completed and approved before DER enrollment in the Aggregation System. The process uses interconnection study data to validate DER characteristics. Aggregators must provide additional interconnection information to the Distribution Utility if requested. The focus is on facility-level requirements, not asset-level, and specific requirements apply to resources with energy duration limitations. DER facilities solely comprising Demand Side Resources are exempt from certain interconnection studies. A diagram illustrates the relationship between assets, DER facilities, and aggregation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Aggregation_Manual/page_23.jpg",
          "page_num": 23,
          "title": "Aggregation Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "05c343d7-1eb2-41a2-a91a-f349d2804c24",
        "score": 0.5611447,
        "text": "The document page outlines the acceptable telemetry communication pathways between the New York ISO (NYISO), Aggregators, and Member Systems. It includes a diagram showing two communication models: one where the Aggregator communicates directly with the NYISO and another where communication is routed through the Member System.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Communication Requirements**: Aggregators must establish communication with the Member System, meeting its requirements through installation, configuration, and testing of necessary hardware.\n\n2. **Direct Communication**: Aggregators can communicate directly with the NYISO using Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) or Software-Defined Wide Area Network (SD-WAN) networks. The Inter-Control Center Communications Protocol (ICCP) is used for two-way communication over MPLS, while ICCP or DNP3 is used for SD-WAN.\n\n3. **Parallel Communication**: Aggregators must maintain a parallel communication connection with the Member System.\n\n4. **Testing Procedure**: The NYISO will initiate telemetry communication tests after enrollment data is submitted and approved. Testing should begin one month before the first month of Distributed Energy Resource (DER) participation in the market. Communication connections must be established before enrollment or data import to the NYISO\u2019s Aggregation System.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Aggregation_Manual/page_67.jpg",
          "page_num": 67,
          "title": "Aggregation Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7e1da819-1e4b-42d9-b76b-7225657a28dc",
        "score": 0.5422938,
        "text": "The document outlines the procedures and requirements for submitting DMNC (Dependable Maximum Net Capability) or DMGC (Dependable Maximum Generating Capacity) test data or data from actual operations to the New York ISO (NYISO). Key points include:\n\n1. **Submission Requirements**: Failure to submit the required data or a completed supplemental form may result in financial penalties.\n\n2. **Purpose**: The data is used to establish a generating resource's Installed Capacity value, which is adjusted according to specific sections of the ICAP Manual.\n\n3. **Validation Process**: Submitted data must be complete and in an acceptable format. NYISO will validate and approve or reject the data within 30 days.\n\n4. **Discrepancies**: Any discrepancies between submitted data and NYISO billing information must be resolved through an audit process within the 30-day period.\n\n5. **Approval and Rejection**: If approved, the data is valid for the current Capability Period. If rejected, the supplier can resubmit data, accept NYISO's determined value, or request an audit.\n\n6. **Audit Process**: If an audit is requested, NYISO will work with the supplier. If the audit supports the supplier's data, the original rating remains. If not, the supplier must resubmit data, and deficiency charges may apply.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_85.jpg",
          "page_num": 85,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "11dff9a6-8791-4982-a3f6-76dc13a56690",
        "score": 0.5398513,
        "text": "The document page outlines two data specifications related to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO):\n\n1. **NYISO Data Specification (Section 4.3):** This provides Market Participants with a reference document detailing where data requests exist within NYISO's processes. It includes an overview of submitting data to NYISO in line with NERC Standard IRO-010 Requirements and NYISO Tariff provisions. Detailed information is available in the referenced processes or documentation.\n\n2. **New York Local Control Center (LCC) Data Specification (Section 4.4):** This offers New York Transmission Owners, who are also NERC registered Transmission Operators, a reference for submitting data to NYISO according to NERC Standard TOP-003 Requirements.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reliability_Compliance_and_Enforcement_Manual/page_14.jpg",
          "page_num": 14,
          "title": "Reliability Compliance and Enforcement Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "652b35ce-564f-49a2-96b3-81d35d8aa225",
        "score": 0.5336763,
        "text": "The document outlines requirements for establishing communication between a DSASP Provider and the New York ISO. Key points include:\n\n1. **Communication Configuration**:\n   - Required if the DSASP Provider's total enrollment is \u2264 25 MW.\n   - Involves one communications vendor, a set of network components, and one ICCP node.\n   - The DSASP Provider and NYISO must complete vendor agreements for direct communications.\n\n2. **Hardware and Software Requirements**:\n   - Establish a contract with a communications vendor to link to NYISO.\n   - Select circuit type, bandwidth, and obtain a Virtual Private LAN Service or MPLS.\n   - Identify network hardware, ensuring routers support encryption and firewalls are recommended.\n   - Software must support ICCP communication as both client and server.\n   - Configure hardware/software for ICCP Node, collaborating with NYISO personnel.\n   - Ensure scalability and redundancy, with systems designed for 99.99% availability.\n   - Identify necessary servers and hardware based on software vendor requirements.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Manual_2_Ancillary_Services_Manual/page_91.jpg",
          "page_num": 91,
          "title": "Manual 2 Ancillary Services Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6b33df2d-f018-4515-b9c7-718d3e9b1b71",
        "score": 0.52468544,
        "text": "The document is a section from an agreement related to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) and its market participants. It includes the following key points:\n\n1. **Liability Release**: Market participants release NYISO and its affiliates from liability, except in cases of gross negligence or intentional misconduct.\n\n2. **Miscellaneous Provisions**:\n   - **Communications**: Details how inquiries, notices, and communications should be exchanged between NYISO and market participants, including contact information for NYISO.\n   - **Survival of Terms**: All representations, warranties, covenants, and obligations remain effective beyond the purchase or sale of Unforced Capacity.\n   - **Entire Agreement**: The agreement, along with the ICAP Manual and ISO Services Tariff, constitutes the full agreement, superseding prior discussions.\n   - **Enforcement**: The agreement's provisions are enforceable for the benefit of both parties.\n   - **Governing Law**: The agreement is governed by New York State law, without regard to conflict of laws provisions.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual_Attachments/page_19.jpg",
          "page_num": 19,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual Attachments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4836b80f-d113-4fe0-a01d-5497adf382b8",
        "score": 0.52223796,
        "text": "The document introduces the transition from the New York Power Pool (NYPP) to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) in late 1999. The NYPP operated a centralized power system using a hierarchical Energy Management System (EMS) with each utility maintaining a SCADA system for data acquisition and control signal distribution. After the NYPP's dissolution, many independent generating plants were built, and existing plants were sold to private entities. This necessitated the integration of new plants into the network for participation in Economic Dispatch Control (EDC) and Automatic Generation Control (AGC).\n\nTo address these changes, the Direct Generator Communications Project was initiated, allowing plants to communicate directly with NYISO. The document outlines the Direct Communications Procedure, which details facilities for generation owners and other suppliers, the Initial Installation Procedure, and Operational Procedures for communications. This procedure is secured and not available online, requiring contact with NYISO for access. The term \"Supplier\" is used throughout the document and the procedure.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Direct_Communications_Manual/page_6.jpg",
          "page_num": 6,
          "title": "Direct Communications Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "94b5a1ce-f64e-4a62-afab-64300e5604df",
        "score": 0.5197011,
        "text": "The document outlines the process for monthly certification of Unforced Capacity (UCAP) by Installed Capacity Suppliers to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). Suppliers must certify that their UCAP is not already committed to other requirements by a specified deadline, as detailed in the ICAP Event Calendar. Suppliers with rights to Unforced Deliverability Rights (UDRs) from external areas must confirm non-use for self-supply by the May certification deadline. Suppliers with derated capacity must demonstrate they have procured additional UCAP to cover any shortfall.\n\nIf a supplier sells UCAP, they remain responsible for its certification unless a bilateral agreement or auction covers it. If UCAP includes New Special Case Resources, the original seller retains certification responsibility. If a bilateral transaction is unconfirmed, the responsibility remains with the supplier who submitted it.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_127.jpg",
          "page_num": 127,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "111dddfd-a669-4d53-a951-5b85cf7be409",
        "score": 0.5188774,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to Installed Capacity Suppliers in the New York City locality, focusing on FERC-approved Unforced Capacity price caps. It lists specific generators subject to these caps, including Arthur Kill Units, Astoria Units, and others.\n\nSection 4 discusses Award Notices, detailing how the ISO communicates with Bidders and Offerors about Unforced Capacity transactions. Notices include information on the amount of capacity, market clearing prices, and total purchase or selling prices. Dispute resolution procedures are also mentioned.\n\nSection 5 covers the posting of auction results, specifying the type of information that will be made available.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual_Attachments/page_35.jpg",
          "page_num": 35,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual Attachments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b29e033b-f5aa-4591-9721-45a301caa65c",
        "score": 0.5186823,
        "text": "The document page is from the New York ISO's Transmission and Dispatch Operations Manual. It is titled \"Attachment A Transmission Facilities\" and outlines three tables:\n\n1. **Table A.1**: Lists NYISO facilities that require coordination and notification.\n2. **Table A.2**: Lists bus voltage limits.\n3. **Table A.3**: Lists bus voltage limits specifically for HQ-NYISO transfers.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Transmission_and_Dispatch_Operations_Manual/page_153.jpg",
          "page_num": 153,
          "title": "Transmission and Dispatch Operations Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

