        "id": "4836b80f-d113-4fe0-a01d-5497adf382b8",
        "score": 0.52223796,
        "text": "The document introduces the transition from the New York Power Pool (NYPP) to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) in late 1999. The NYPP operated a centralized power system using a hierarchical Energy Management System (EMS) with each utility maintaining a SCADA system for data acquisition and control signal distribution. After the NYPP's dissolution, many independent generating plants were built, and existing plants were sold to private entities. This necessitated the integration of new plants into the network for participation in Economic Dispatch Control (EDC) and Automatic Generation Control (AGC).\n\nTo address these changes, the Direct Generator Communications Project was initiated, allowing plants to communicate directly with NYISO. The document outlines the Direct Communications Procedure, which details facilities for generation owners and other suppliers, the Initial Installation Procedure, and Operational Procedures for communications. This procedure is secured and not available online, requiring contact with NYISO for access. The term \"Supplier\" is used throughout the document and the procedure.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Direct_Communications_Manual/page_6.jpg",
          "page_num": 6,
          "title": "Direct Communications Manual",
