    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "e265fb5b-5098-4f8a-8529-b45dfcab7939",
        "score": 0.6093361,
        "text": "The document page presents data on uplift costs from guarantee payments in New York, categorized by region and year (2018-2019). The chart shows costs in millions of dollars for New York City, Long Island, East Upstate, West Upstate, and Imports, with a total for each year. In 2019, the total was $52 million, down from $77 million in 2018. Long Island's costs remained stable at $15 million each year, with a significant portion (67%) attributed to high-cost peaking resources managing congestion and voltage needs. Recommendations include modeling specific constraints to improve market efficiency and reliability.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2019/page_125.jpg",
          "page_num": 125,
          "title": "2019 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "2418dcc9-c47f-4f11-8e00-9e2963db9b4d",
        "score": 0.5772172,
        "text": "The document page discusses the uplift costs from guarantee payments in New York for the years 2016 and 2017. In 2017, the total uplift cost was $38 million, a 12% decrease from 2016's $43 million. The decline was mainly in Western New York, which saw a 49% reduction, and Long Island, with a 38% reduction. These reductions were due to less reliability commitment and out-of-market (OOM) dispatch. The local uplift in Western New York decreased significantly due to transmission upgrades and the expiration of the Milliken RSSA. The remaining local uplift could be eliminated if constraints were modeled in NYISO\u2019s day-ahead and real-time markets.\n\nAdditionally, the DAMAP, Min Oil Burn, and EDRP/SCR categories saw a reduction of over $5 million. Most uplift charges in 2016 occurred during high load days in July and August, which were not present in 2017 due to milder weather.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2017/page_109.jpg",
          "page_num": 109,
          "title": "2017 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d7757b83-44bd-4712-8bc7-1e297d7de467",
        "score": 0.5743052,
        "text": "The document page presents data on uplift costs from guarantee payments for the years 2017 and 2018, divided into two figures.\n\n**Figure A-90: Uplift Costs by Month (2017-2018)**\n- Displays monthly uplift costs categorized by type: Day Ahead, Real Time, DAMAP, Min Oil, and EDRP/SCR.\n- Costs are further divided into Local and Statewide categories.\n- Total costs for 2018 were $77 million, while 2017 totaled $38 million.\n- The chart shows monthly variations, with a significant spike in December 2017.\n\n**Figure A-91: Uplift Costs by Region (2017-2018)**\n- Shows uplift costs by region: New York City, Long Island, East Upstate, West Upstate, Imports, and EDRP/SCR.\n- Costs are broken down by categories similar to Figure A-90.\n- Total costs for 2018 were $77 million, compared to $38 million in 2017.\n- New York City had the highest costs in both years, with notable increases in 2018.\n\nBoth figures illustrate the distribution and variation of costs over time and by region, highlighting significant differences between the two years.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2018/page_318.jpg",
          "page_num": 318,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "14a3f2e3-fafe-4901-874e-a94ec44c6355",
        "score": 0.5715088,
        "text": "This document page discusses deliverability and transmission planning related to the interconnection of energy projects, focusing on the categories of upgrades identified in the Cluster Study and Class Year process. The key points include:\n\n1. **Categories of Upgrades:**\n   - **Connecting Transmission Owner\u2019s Attachment Facilities (CTOAF):** Facilities required to connect a project to the transmission owner's network.\n   - **System Upgrade Facilities (SUF):** Network upgrades needed for projects to comply with NYISO\u2019s Minimum Interconnection Standard (MIS). Projects must pay allocated costs to receive the right to sell energy (ERIS). The MIS addresses reliability impacts but allows normal operating actions to avoid adverse effects.\n   - **System Deliverability Upgrades (SDU):** Upgrades required for resources to be deliverable under NYISO\u2019s Deliverability Interconnection Standard (DIS). Projects must pay for these upgrades to receive the right to sell capacity (CRIS). The DIS ensures that new and existing resources can deliver output without violating transmission constraints.\n\n2. **Process and Costs:**\n   - Developers must decide whether to pay for upgrades to receive ERIS or CRIS rights or withdraw from the study.\n   - The number of resources seeking interconnection and upgrade costs have increased recently.\n   - Class Year studies typically take about two years, while the Cluster Study aims for a 590-day timeline.\n   - New resources not part of an ongoing study must wait for a new study to begin.\n   - If SDUs are needed, a preliminary cost estimate is issued, and affected projects may enter an Additional SDU Study for final cost allocations.\n\n3. **Inefficient Upgrade Project Selection \u2013 Class Year 2023:**\n   - The most recent Class Year study (2023) started in January 2023 and finished in early 2025.\n   - Participants requested about 15 GW of ERIS and 14 GW of CRIS.\n   - The study identified $2.8 billion in CTOAF and SUF costs, with individual cost allocations ranging from $0 to $581 per kW of nameplate capacity, averaging $207 per kW.\n   - Proposed projects were generally fully deliverable except on Long Island, where an Additional SDU Study was necessary.\n\nThe page also includes references to additional details on the interconnection process and related study reports available on NYISO\u2019s website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/NYISO/report/2024/page_50.jpg",
          "page_num": 50,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9a7044c5-f6d8-442f-8620-8b17231a60b3",
        "score": 0.5662533,
        "text": "The document discusses the evaluation of market incentives for modeling N-1-1 requirements in New York City's day-ahead market by estimating clearing prices for 2018. It presents a summary of results for four NYC locations: the 345kV network in Staten Island, Astoria West/Queensbridge, Vernon, and Greenwood/Staten Island. The table shows average marginal commitment costs, with prices ranging from $2.01/MWh for the NYC 345 kV System to $5.18/MWh for Astoria West/Queensbridge.\n\nThe analysis indicates that satisfying N-1-1 requirements would lead to price increases, with costs varying from $2.01 to $5.18 per MWh. These increases are additional to existing reserve product prices in Southeast New York. The document also examines the impact on energy and reserve net revenues if units were compensated for reserves at these rates.\n\nRecommendations include modeling N-1-1 constraints in NYC load pockets to enhance market efficiency and reliability. The NYISO plans to introduce a 10-minute and a 30-minute reserve product for NYC in mid-2019, aiming for more efficient scheduling and pricing.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2018/page_116.jpg",
          "page_num": 116,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1fe556ac-9444-4fff-be8b-78b250cdcb0c",
        "score": 0.5660479,
        "text": "The document discusses the System Deliverability Upgrade (SDU) Study, which identifies necessary upgrades for resources to meet the New York Independent System Operator\u2019s (NYISO) Deliverability Interconnection Standard. Developers must pay for these upgrades to obtain the right to sell capacity. After a Class Year Study, developers decide whether to pay for upgrades, receive rights, or withdraw. The number of resources and costs in these studies have increased, taking about two years to complete.\n\nThe results of the Class Year 2021 (CY21) are detailed. The study began in February 2021 and concluded in January 2023, with participants requesting 11 GW of ERIS and 10 GW of CRIS. The study identified $900 million in required upgrades, with $800 million for direct project connections and $100 million for systemwide reliability. Sixteen projects, totaling over 4 GW of CRIS, were not fully deliverable. NYISO identified $1.5 billion in SDUs for these projects, with costs ranging from $468 to $2,557 per kW of UCAP. These costs are shown over a 20-year period as a percentage of the 2022/23 capacity market net CONE.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2022/page_58.jpg",
          "page_num": 58,
          "title": "2022 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0ae21349-5a7a-4dce-b74d-9e981b8af7aa",
        "score": 0.564454,
        "text": "The document page provides data on uplift costs from guarantee payments for the years 2016 and 2017, presented in two figures.\n\n1. **Figure A-84**: This figure shows uplift costs by month, categorized by local and statewide payments. The categories include Day Ahead, Real Time, DAMAP (Day-Ahead Margin Assurance Payment), and EDRP/SCR (Emergency Demand Response Program/Special Case Resources). The total uplift costs were $43 million in 2016 and $38 million in 2017.\n\n2. **Figure A-85**: This figure breaks down uplift costs by region, including New York City, Long Island, East Upstate, West Upstate, and Imports. The costs are further categorized by the same payment types as in Figure A-84. In 2016, the total was $43 million, while in 2017, it was $38 million.\n\nBoth figures highlight variations in costs across different months and regions, with detailed breakdowns of the specific categories contributing to the total uplift costs. The note clarifies that the figures are based on available information at the reporting time and may differ from final settlements due to manual adjustments.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2017/page_293.jpg",
          "page_num": 293,
          "title": "2017 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "96157d41-d569-4f5d-a316-a39cf082b65a",
        "score": 0.56031674,
        "text": "The document page provides a detailed analysis of the cost and performance parameters of renewable energy units, specifically utility-scale solar PV, onshore wind, and offshore wind. \n\n### Table A-21: Cost and Performance Parameters\n- **Investment Cost (2019$/kW AC basis):**\n  - Utility-Scale Solar PV: Upstate NY - $1458, Long Island - $1897\n  - Onshore Wind: Upstate NY - $1767, Long Island - $2384\n  - Offshore Wind: NYC/Long Island - $4571\n\n- **Fixed O&M (2019$/kW-yr):**\n  - Solar PV: $18\n  - Onshore Wind: $50\n  - Offshore Wind: $127\n\n- **Federal Incentives:**\n  - Solar PV and Offshore Wind: ITC\n  - Onshore Wind: PTC\n\n- **Project Life:** 20 years\n- **Depreciation Schedule:** 5-years MACRS\n\n- **Average Annual Capacity Factor:**\n  - Solar PV: Upstate NY - 16.4%, Long Island - 17.9%\n  - Onshore Wind: Upstate NY - 36.0%, Long Island - 40.0%\n  - Offshore Wind: NYC/Long Island - 45.9%\n\n- **Unforced Capacity Percentage:**\n  - Solar PV: Summer - 46%, Winter - 2%\n  - Onshore Wind: Summer - 10%, Winter - 30%\n  - Offshore Wind: Summer - 38%, Winter - 38%\n\n- **Renewable Energy Credits (Nominal $/MWh):**\n  - Onshore Wind and Solar PV: 2020 - $22.09, 2019 - $22.43, 2018 - $17.01, 2017 - $21.16\n  - Offshore Wind: Calculated using a strike price of $88/MWh NYC / $96/MWh LI (2018$)\n\n### Figure A-111: Net Revenues of Solar, Onshore Wind, and Offshore Wind Units (2017-2022)\n- The graph illustrates net revenues and estimated CONE (Cost of New Entry) for each unit type from 2017 to 2022.\n- Components include capacity spot auction, E&AS net revenue, renewable energy credits, PTC revenue/ITC offset, estimated CONE, and CONE with full expensing.\n\nThe document assumes that the operating and cost parameters are consistent with the table, and the net revenues and estimated CONE reflect those of a representative unit commencing operation in the same year.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2019/page_375.jpg",
          "page_num": 375,
          "title": "2019 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e1faf5de-3161-4645-a8ee-2f23b2e86a40",
        "score": 0.5601442,
        "text": "The document page presents data on uplift costs from guarantee payments for the years 2012 and 2013, divided into two figures.\n\n**Figure A-90: Uplift Costs from Guarantee Payments by Month (2012-2013)**\n- This bar chart shows monthly uplift costs categorized by different payment types: DAM Local, DAM Statewide, DAMAP Local, DAMAP Statewide, RT Local, RT Statewide, Min Oil Burn, and EDRP/SCR.\n- The costs are further divided into local and statewide categories, with a total for each year.\n- In 2013, the total uplift cost was $164 million, while in 2012, it was $146 million.\n- The chart indicates fluctuations in costs throughout the months, with noticeable peaks in certain months.\n\n**Figure A-91: Uplift Costs from Guarantee Payments by Region (2012-2013)**\n- This bar chart displays uplift costs by region: New York City, Long Island, East Upstate, West Upstate, and Imports.\n- The costs are broken down by the same categories as in Figure A-90.\n- In 2013, New York City had the highest uplift cost at $65 million, followed by Long Island at $51 million.\n- The chart shows quarterly data for each region, highlighting variations in costs across different areas and time periods.\n\nOverall, the document provides a detailed breakdown of uplift costs by month and region, illustrating trends and differences in guarantee payments over the two years.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2013/page_271.jpg",
          "page_num": 271,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2013,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "47565ab1-a9c3-4f02-a05a-d9f09e29792c",
        "score": 0.55386716,
        "text": "The document page is an appendix from the 2017 State of the Market Report, focusing on net revenue analysis for renewable energy units. It includes a table (Table A-16) detailing the cost and performance parameters for utility-scale solar PV, onshore wind, and offshore wind units. Key parameters include:\n\n- **Investment Cost (2017$/kW AC):** Varies by location, with solar PV costs ranging from $1,589 to $2,475, onshore wind from $1,858 to $2,820, and offshore wind at $5,635.\n- **Fixed O&M (2017$/kW-yr):** $17 for solar PV, $58 for onshore wind, and $161 for offshore wind.\n- **Federal Incentives:** ITC (30%) for solar and offshore wind, PTC ($23/MWh) for onshore wind.\n- **Project Life:** 20 years.\n- **Depreciation Schedule:** 5-year MACRS.\n- **Average Annual Capacity Factor:** Varies by region, with solar PV ranging from 17.0% to 17.6%, onshore wind from 38.0% to 39.9%, and offshore wind at 45.9%.\n- **Unforced Capacity Percentage:** Varies by season and type.\n- **Renewable Energy Credits (Nominal $/MWh):** Listed for years 2015-2018.\n\nThe page also includes Figure A-106, which shows net revenues and estimated CONE for these units from 2015 to 2020, based on the operating and cost parameters provided. Additional notes discuss assumptions for investment costs, interconnection costs, and construction lead times.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2017/page_340.jpg",
          "page_num": 340,
          "title": "2017 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

