    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "0f82e777-494c-4a13-9fbf-c9274e316dc8",
        "score": 0.58489025,
        "text": "The document page is a table of contents from the New York ISO Reference Level Manual. It outlines sections related to energy bidding and cost data management. Key sections include:\n\n- **Fuel Cost Adjustments**: Discusses NYISO's automated screening limits and the submission process for energy bids exceeding $1000/MWh, including required documentation.\n- **Start-Up Cost Data**: Covers general descriptions, RLS data requirements, and necessary documentation.\n- **Variable Cost Data**: Details operating, maintenance, and regulatory costs, along with RLS data and documentation requirements.\n- **Risk & Opportunity Cost Data**: Includes descriptions, dynamic opportunity costs for ESR generators, and adjustments, with data and documentation requirements.\n- **Reference Level Development for Demand-Side Resources**: Mentions an introduction, but the section is marked with an error.\n\nEach section provides guidelines and requirements for managing energy costs and bids within the NYISO framework.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_4.jpg",
          "page_num": 4,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4b1f14bc-1d8b-4123-9aed-cc9c714ab763",
        "score": 0.5779195,
        "text": "The document discusses the impact of fees on transactions between control areas, specifically between New York and New England. In 2005, export fees between these regions were eliminated to facilitate market arbitrage, but other charges remain. These charges, related to ISO/RTO operating costs, were initially based on the largest transaction of the month, leading to high costs for some participants. To address this, an alternative per MWh allocation method was introduced. Despite these changes, significant price dispersion and seams issues persist, hindering efficient market interchange. The document highlights the importance of efficient scheduling during peak demand and examines price differences in unconstrained hours when prices exceed $200/MWh.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2005/page_145.jpg",
          "page_num": 145,
          "title": "2005 State of the Market Report New York ISO",
          "year": 2005,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d5b29f8d-c4cf-4d57-a755-1f6969f46e53",
        "score": 0.57689667,
        "text": "The document page outlines the annual budget charge and other non-budget charges and payments for services provided by the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). It categorizes these charges into three main areas: \n\n1. **Physical Operation of the NY Control Area**\n2. **Administration of NYISO tariffs and related agreements**\n3. **Other Non-Budget Charges**\n\nDetails of these services are found in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the Accounting and Billing Manual.\n\n**Recovery of NYISO Costs**: Information on cost recovery is available in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the NYISO Services Tariff.\n\n**Payment for Service**: Payment details are also in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the NYISO Services Tariff.\n\n**Services at the Request of a Market Participant**: Market participants can request and pay for specific NYISO services, including:\n\n- System Reliability Impact Study (ESRIS)\n- Facilities Study\n- Local Control Center operator training\n- Re-enforcement Option Study (also requested by PSC)\n- System Impact Study\n- Interconnection Study",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Manual_2_Ancillary_Services_Manual/page_36.jpg",
          "page_num": 36,
          "title": "Manual 2 Ancillary Services Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d157906c-6a83-474e-962b-ef2e97d23161",
        "score": 0.57548976,
        "text": "The document page is from the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) and pertains to the Transmission Congestion Contracts Manual. It includes the following details:\n\n- **Version**: 5.0\n- **Effective Date**: January 2, 2024\n- **Committee Acceptance**: December 13, 2023, by the BIC\n- **Recertified**: January 2, 2024\n- **Prepared By**: NYISO TCC Market Operations\n\nThe contact information for NYISO is provided:\n\n- Address: 10 Krey Boulevard, Rensselaer, NY 12144\n- Phone: (518) 356-6060\n- Website: www.nyiso.com\n\nA disclaimer notes that the information is for informational purposes only, subject to change, and NYISO is not responsible for reliance on the material. The document is copyrighted from 1999-2024 by the New York Independent System Operator.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Transmission_Congestion_Contracts_Manual/page_2.jpg",
          "page_num": 2,
          "title": "Transmission Congestion Contracts Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "5b6b3fc8-4b92-4f10-8042-1cbb054c1139",
        "score": 0.5719835,
        "text": "The document is a Table of Contents from the New York ISO Reference Level Manual. It includes the following sections:\n\n1. **Introduction**: \n   - Purpose and audience of the manual.\n\n2. **Reference Level Consultations**: \n   - Description, process and timelines, review guidelines, and operational metrics.\n\n3. **NYISO-Initiated Reference Level Consultations**: \n   - Description and process and timelines.\n\n4. **Mitigation Consultations**: \n   - Description, process and timelines, review guidelines, and operational metrics.\n\n5. **Heat Rate Data**: \n   - General description, data requirements for Reference Level Software (RLS), and required documentation, including incremental heat rate curves and input-output curves.\n\n6. **Fuel & Emission Cost Data**: \n   - General description, fuel cost adders and multipliers, and fuel cost adjustments.\n\nThe document provides a structured overview of the topics covered in the manual, focusing on consultations, data requirements, and cost data.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_3.jpg",
          "page_num": 3,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "14084d67-b441-47f8-b65c-72a5073179c1",
        "score": 0.56908596,
        "text": "The document page is a table of contents from the New York ISO Reference Level Manual. It outlines sections related to developing reference costs and levels for energy resources. Key sections include:\n\n- **10.2**: Method for developing reference costs for incremental energy and minimum generation for demand-side resources.\n- **11**: Reference level development for aggregations and hybrid storage resources, including an introduction and methods for developing reference levels.\n- **12**: Ancillary services, focusing on regulation movement, with subsections on cost overview, components, submission forms, and cost translation into costs per MW-Hr.\n- **Appendix A**: Variable cost categories.\n\nThe page numbers for each section are also provided.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_5.jpg",
          "page_num": 5,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b164d87f-9ccf-468c-8cb0-176f30fb3261",
        "score": 0.5654989,
        "text": "The document page discusses the requirements for suppliers to provide the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) with documentation of costs related to maintenance activities as defined in the Long-Term Service Agreement (LTSA). It specifies that suppliers can include cost escalators in their submissions if they are part of the LTSA. Suppliers must submit contracts to demonstrate the variability of costs, which are subject to review by NYISO and its Market Monitoring Unit (MMU) for reasonableness and appropriateness. The NYISO allows the inclusion of certain costs, like fuel management fees, in cost-based references when presented on a per mmBTU basis.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_38.jpg",
          "page_num": 38,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "54f44bbb-43c1-4f81-ba41-e8f8258844ee",
        "score": 0.5639609,
        "text": "The document outlines the process for submitting cost components related to Regulation Movement to the NYISO. It emphasizes the need for both quantitative and qualitative data from Market Participants. Quantitative estimates should follow a specific framework:\n\n1. **Thermal Losses**: \n   - Report additional mmBTUs consumed during regulation for one hour.\n   - Calculate the percentage increase in fuel consumption using a ratio of additional mmBTUs consumed during regulation to total mmBTUs consumed when not on regulation.\n\n2. **Maintenance Costs**:\n   - Provide the dollar amount of additional maintenance costs per hour of regulation.\n   - Calculate the percentage increase in maintenance costs by comparing additional costs during regulation to costs when not on regulation.\n\nThe NYISO will calculate Regulation Movement costs per MW-hr using:\n- Burdened fuel cost information for thermal losses.\n- Heat rate data for thermal losses.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_48.jpg",
          "page_num": 48,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "154fabdc-bfab-42a1-936f-630e45868f98",
        "score": 0.5627301,
        "text": "The document page is from the New York ISO Transmission Congestion Contracts Manual. It discusses the provision of rules, procedures, and guidelines for new auction formats. The section titled \"References\" lists documents and resources available on the NYISO website that provide additional background or details related to the manual. These include:\n\n- Open Access Transmission Tariff\n- NYISO Market Administration and Control Area Services Tariff\n- NYISO Accounting and Billing Manual\n- Transmission Congestion Contracts page\n- NYISO Customer Registration\n- TCC Automated Market System User\u2019s Guide\n- Credit Management System User\u2019s Guide\n- Settlement Data Applications User\u2019s Guide\n\nThese resources are intended to support understanding and implementation of the manual's content.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Transmission_Congestion_Contracts_Manual/page_24.jpg",
          "page_num": 24,
          "title": "Transmission Congestion Contracts Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b0ba2f85-04f5-4ab4-bb03-1c23e15733a2",
        "score": 0.5592999,
        "text": "The document page presents data on Transmission Congestion Contracts (TCC) costs and profits for both inter-zonal and intra-zonal paths during the Winter 2017/18 and Summer 2018 capability periods. \n\n### Key Points:\n\n1. **Inter-Zone Data:**\n   - **One Year:** Cost is $58 million with a profit of $12 million, yielding a 21% profit as a percentage of cost.\n   - **Six-Month Winter:** Cost is $90 million with a loss of $1 million, resulting in a -1% profit.\n   - **Six-Month Summer:** Cost is $44 million with a profit of $19 million, yielding a 43% profit.\n   - **Monthly Winter:** Cost is $6 million with a profit of $1 million, yielding a 12% profit.\n   - **Monthly Summer:** Cost is $9 million with a loss of $1 million, resulting in a -12% profit.\n   - **Total:** Overall cost is $206 million with a profit of $30 million, yielding a 15% profit.\n\n2. **Intra-Zone Data:**\n   - **One Year:** Cost is $17 million with a profit of $3 million, yielding an 18% profit.\n   - **Six-Month Winter:** Cost is $5 million with a profit of $4 million, yielding a 79% profit.\n   - **Six-Month Summer:** Cost is $12 million with a profit of $7 million, yielding a 56% profit.\n   - **Monthly Winter:** Cost is $6 million with a profit of $1 million, yielding a 12% profit.\n   - **Monthly Summer:** Cost is $5 million with a profit of $2 million, yielding a 37% profit.\n   - **Total:** Overall cost is $46 million with a profit of $16 million, yielding a 36% profit.\n\n3. **Visual Representation:**\n   - The bar chart illustrates TCC costs and profits for different auction rounds and path types, with inter-zonal and intra-zonal paths compared.\n\n4. **Color Coding:**\n   - TCC costs and profits higher than $2 million are highlighted in green.\n   - TCC costs and profits lower than -$2 million are highlighted in light red.\n\nThis data is part of the 2018 State of the Market Report, focusing on transmission congestion.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2018/page_230.jpg",
          "page_num": 230,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

